<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-437-510  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 437 510.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  May 7 1990 v11 n19 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Decentralization trend mirrors societal changes.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Puttre, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Decentralization of MIS departments mirrors the sociologicalconcept of demassification, a process by which all elements ofsociety are being broken down into smaller, interactive units.andO;Resistance to such change is basic to human nature, leaving MISmanagement faced with the task of reducing the conflict caused bydemassification of information systems.andP;  MIS must regarddemassification as part of the natural evolution of informationsystems, rather than as a challenge to its authority.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     DecentralizationMISManagement.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>